This course aims to provide an overview of a number of protracted regional conflicts in Eurasia. We will examine closely conflicts ranging from North and South Caucasus to Transnistria, and from Ukraine/Crimea to Central Asia, from the collapse of the Soviet Union until today. More specifically, we will apply conflict assessment toolbox, and analyse dividers and connectors, principal players and secondary actors, drivers of conflict and peace, and finally, windows of vulnerability and opportunity in these regional conflicts.Objectives/eesmärkid:  This course aims to provide an overview of a number of protracted regional conflicts in Eurasia, to introduce their key players and their main stakes, and to critically analyse the conflict management perspectives. The course seeks to apply conflict assessment toolbox in the empirical analysis of the post-Soviet region conflicts.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Upon completion of the course, the students will: 1) have a comprehensive empirical understanding of the major regional conflicts in the former Soviet space; 2) be able to analyse these frozen and on-going conflicts through conflict assessment toolbox; 3) situate the texts read in the framework of the course and their authors in wider intellectual contexts;  4) formulate, present and defend specific arguments in oral and written formats alike; 5) put forth a clear and well-argued policy advice on conflict management.
